{"result": "**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Make or Buy-in\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Make or Buy-in is a decision-making process where a company decides whether to produce a product internally or purchase it from an external supplier. This involves comparing the costs saved if in-house production ceases, including any incremental fixed costs, with the costs of buying the component from an external supplier.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Example of Make or Buy-in\"<|>\"examples\"<|>\"Geranium Co makes a product that requires two sequential operations on the same machine. Operation 1 takes 15 minutes per unit, and Operation 2 takes 30 minutes per unit. The machine is operating at full capacity. The material cost of the product is $12 per unit. Instead of carrying out Operation 1, Geranium could buy in components for $15 per unit. This would increase production capacity because the machine has to deal with only Operation 2. Labour and variable overheads are incurred at a rate of $16 per machine hour, and the finished products sell for $30 per unit.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Outsourcing All Production\"<|>\"quizzes\"<|>\"The quiz for outsourcing all production involves determining the costs saved if the offer to outsource is accepted and advising whether to continue manufacturing in-house or outsource. It includes a scenario where Big Phones must decide whether to manufacture batteries in-house or buy them from Super Batteries.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"In decision making, relevant costs and revenues are those which change as a result of the decision. All other revenues and costs are ignored.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Opportunity cost\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"An opportunity cost is a benefit foregone. Opportunity costs are relevant costs.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Decision-making scenarios\"<|>\"features\"<|>\"Decision-making scenarios include 'one-off contracts' which require the calculation of the relevant cost of performing a contract. A relevant cost may be a current (replacement) cost or an opportunity cost (which may be zero). The deprival value of a non-current asset is the lower of its replacement cost and value in use. Value in use is the higher of net realisable value and economic value. In shut down decisions, costs of the loss-making division that will not be saved are irrelevant to the decision. Further processing decisions consider whether further processing of joint- or by-products is worthwhile. To buy-in rather than make a product is an outsourcing decision.\")**##**(\"entity\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit Analysis\"<|>\"concepts\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit (CVP) Analysis is a method used to understand the relationship between costs, volume, and profit in decision-making. It involves calculating and interpreting the breakeven point, margin of safety, contribution to sales ratio, target profit or revenue, and interpreting breakeven and profit volume charts.\")**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Make or Buy-in\"<|>\"Example of Make or Buy-in\"<|>\"Make or Buy-in includes an example of Make or Buy-in decision involving Geranium Co.\" <|> 8)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Outsourcing All Production\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues\"<|>\"The quiz on outsourcing all production involves determining relevant costs and revenues.\" <|> 7)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues\"<|>\"Opportunity cost\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues include opportunity costs.\" <|> 9)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Decision-making scenarios\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues\"<|>\"Decision-making scenarios involve the calculation of relevant costs and revenues.\" <|> 8)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit Analysis\"<|>\"Decision-making scenarios\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit Analysis is a decision-making technique that involves understanding costs, volume, and profit relationships.\" <|> 7)**##**(\"relationship\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit Analysis\"<|>\"Relevant costs and revenues\"<|>\"Cost Volume Profit Analysis involves understa